description:
Sticky header has backdrop-filter: blur(10px) always on. A subtle transition from transparent to frosted as user scrolls would communicate "content sliding behind header."

Implementation:
1. Start header with backdrop-filter: blur(0px) and transparent background
2. Add .scrolled class via JS on scroll (Intersection Observer on a sentinel element, or simple scroll listener with threshold)
3. Transition to blur(10px) + rgba(10,10,10,0.9) over 0.3s
4. Use will-change: backdrop-filter for performance hint

CSS:
header { backdrop-filter: blur(0px); background: transparent; transition: backdrop-filter 0.3s ease, background-color 0.3s ease; }
header.scrolled { backdrop-filter: blur(10px); background: rgba(10, 10, 10, 0.9); }

JS (minimal):
const header = document.querySelector('header');
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
  header.classList.toggle('scrolled', window.scrollY > 20);
}, { passive: true });

